[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring JaCoCo Annotations**\n\nI’m considering whether I can avoid JaCoCo by using an annotation. JaCoCo excludes classes and methods that are annotated with a name containing `Generated` when it comes to reporting, but I’m wondering if that applies to instrumentation as well. It seems like the annotation filters might not stop instrumentation, but I could be mistaken. I also think about making a holder interface, but I’m questioning if JaCoCo even instruments interfaces correctly. There seem to be complexities around initialization as well.\n\n**Analyzing Interface Initializers**\n\nI’m thinking about whether interfaces with class initializers could work. If I use `getDeclaredFields`, it might include the `DEFAULT_ENTRY` and possibly `$jacocoData`, which seems risky. I could create a holder class with just one field, aiming to avoid executable code so that JaCoCo doesn’t insert probes. But then again, does that mean the field needs to be a compile-time constant? The issue here is that the field type has to be a `MapEntry`, which complicates things.\n\n**Evaluating object parsing**\n\nI’m considering whether I need to check for a non-null object using FieldInfo for map fields. It seems like I have to use the existing Struct DEFAULT_ENTRY object during the field initialization with a method call. However, I wonder if calling getMapDefaultEntry might return null later. So, if the field default is null, maybe the forMapField should have a non-null check. I definitely need to read FieldInfo.forMapField to clarify this!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0e0ef4dc3095b7d0016a0f4bbd4c4c8194b986b2d49178cc87\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqD0vKzgc0I2K35TIDuYBw73pQdfw-nF_OpNUpzv_bSCHA93-skgWlbWzTbEWphdWIjLCDZMfkUTHUmLKW_8-rn_vghB1VBwBBQTIdtJa923HbJHgWUct6aXyrUAlr05i3XI0-BOcAqMH9GveLKvjJ5xQg6vaoxeiWFFofs_SV9K3QkOL4CGYraXYtkzQQBXP_a9-CNDQlvW